                  <p align="left"><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><br>
                    enviroLAW contains synopses and checklists of statutory legislation 
                    relevant to <b>Environmental and/or Health &amp; Safety</b> 
                    matters.<br>
                    <br>
                    <b>Statutory law</b> is written law set down by a legislature 
                    or other governing authority such as the executive branch 
                    of government in response to a perceived need to clarify the 
                    functioning of government, improve civil order, answer a public 
                    need, to codify existing law (codification is the process 
                    of collecting and restating the law of a jurisdiction in certain 
                    areas), or for an individual or company to obtain special 
                    treatment. In addition to the statutes passed by the national 
                    or state legislature, lower authorities or municipalities 
                    may also issue administrative regulations or municipal ordinances 
                    that have the force of law - the process of creating these 
                    administrative decrees are generally clasified as rulemaking. 
                    While these enactments are subordinate to the law of the whole 
                    state or nation, they are nonetheless a part of the body of 
                    a jurisdiction's statutory law. </font></p>
                  <p align="left"><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">There 
                    are two main systems of law in operation throughout the world 
                    - those based on the <b>Roman system of civil law</b>, and 
                    those based on the <b>English common law system</b>.<br>
                    <br>
                    European countries, with the exception of the UK &amp; Ireland, 
                    generally use the Roman system, as do latin american countries 
                    and much of Asia, although in the case of the latter custom 
                    also plays an important role.<br>
                    <br>
                    The USA, Canada, UK, Ireland, India and Australia have systems 
                    based on common law.<br>
                    <br>
                    Unlike the Roman system which is mainly based on written civil 
                    codes, the common law system is based in tradition, custom, 
                    and precedent and may be unwritten. Because it has never been 
                    precisely defined or codified, common law is interpreted in 
                    court cases by judges. This so called <b>case law</b> regulates, 
                    via precedents, how laws are to be understood, based on how 
                    prior cases have been decided. Case law governs the impact 
                    court decisions have on future cases.<br>
                    <br>
                    <b>enviroLAW does not include case law.</b><br>
                    <br>
                    Currently enviroLAW PRO covers legislation from the following 
                    jurisdictions: England &amp; Wales, European Union, Germany 
                    (Federal), Ireland, Northern Ireland, Scotland, Spain and 
                    USA. The legislation available to users will however depend 
                    on the Licence Agreement purchased which may include one or 
                    more of the jurisdictions with Environmental and/or Health 
                    &amp; Safety access.</font></p>
